assertives.from: List of assertive verbs extracted from: Joan B. Hooper. 1975. On assertive predicates. In J. Kimball, editor,Syntax and Semantics, volume 4, pages 91–124. Academic Press, New York.
assertives.epbias_def: verbs which presuppose the certainty of a dependent clause that completes the meaning of a noun, adjective, verb, or preposition

entailments.epbias_def: shows directional relations that hold whenever the truth of one word or phrase follows from another.

factives.from: List of factive verbs extracted from: Joan B. Hooper. 1975. On assertive predicates. In J. Kimball, editor,Syntax and Semantics, volume 4, pages 91–124. Academic Press, New York.
factives.epbias_def: presupposes the truth of a dependent clause that completes the meaning of a noun, adjective, verb, or preposition

hedges.from: List of hedges extracted from:Ken Hyland. 2005. Metadiscourse: Exploring Interaction in Writing. Continuum, London and New York.
hedges.epbias_def: reduces commitment to the truth of a proposition

implicatives.from: List of implicative verbs extracted from:Lauri Karttunen. 1971. Implicative verbs. Language, 47(2):340, 2013358.
implicatives.epbias_def: suggests in an utterance, even though neither expressed nor strictly implied

negative.epbias_def: portrays only one side of a contentious issue

positive.epbias_def: portrays only one side of a contentious issue

report.from: List of report verbs used in Marta Recasens, Cristian Danescu-Niculescu-Mizil, and Dan Jurafsky. 2013. Linguistic Models for Analyzing and Detecting Biased Language. Proceedings of ACL 2013.
report.epbias_def: often used in reporting to frame the way viewers understand a matter

subjectives.epbias_def: adjectives or adverbs that add or reduce subjective force to the meaning of a phrase or proposition

boosters.epbias_def: increases commitment to the truth of a proposition

other.epbias_def: Epistemological bias is any word that erodes or asserts a person's capacity as a knower, which can lead to injustice/unfairness
